00:58:42.973 --> 00:58:44.640
I'm going to say a
little bit about sort

00:58:44.640 --> 00:58:48.319
of which route to go when you
want to deal with temperature.

00:58:54.376 --> 00:58:56.250
You know, an obvious
way is always

00:58:56.250 --> 00:58:59.700
to do the direct dynamics
through molecular dynamics.

00:58:59.700 --> 00:59:02.370
It's a powerful approach.

00:59:02.370 --> 00:59:07.110
It's, in particular,
powerful to see phenomena

00:59:07.110 --> 00:59:11.610
that you didn't even know were
there, because in almost all

00:59:11.610 --> 00:59:14.970
the other approximate approaches
we're going to do for dynamics

00:59:14.970 --> 00:59:19.650
or temperature, we're going
to assume that we know

00:59:19.650 --> 00:59:22.350
and understand the phenomena
that are responsible

00:59:22.350 --> 00:59:25.020
for the macroscopic
behavior we see.

00:59:25.020 --> 00:59:26.430
In some sense,
molecular dynamics

00:59:26.430 --> 00:59:30.122
is the only way where
you don't presume much.

00:59:30.122 --> 00:59:32.330
I mean, you presume something
about your Hamiltonian,

00:59:32.330 --> 00:59:33.205
your energy function.

00:59:33.205 --> 00:59:35.790
But otherwise, you just
kind of let the system run,

00:59:35.790 --> 00:59:37.290
and you see what happens.

00:59:37.290 --> 00:59:39.130
What you have to keep
in mind, of course,

00:59:39.130 --> 00:59:46.260
is that the timescale over which
you run is extremely short.

00:59:46.260 --> 00:59:52.320
I mean, you're now living on
the time in the world of atoms.

00:59:52.320 --> 00:59:59.430
And atoms vibrate, let's say,
somewhere between 1 terahertz

00:59:59.430 --> 01:00:00.360
maybe 10 terahertz.

01:00:00.360 --> 01:00:01.568
That's actually pretty high--

01:00:01.568 --> 01:00:03.730
10 terahertz.

01:00:03.730 --> 01:00:08.380
So that would be 10 to
the 13 times per second.

01:00:08.380 --> 01:00:11.200
And remember you have to
integrate equations of motion.

01:00:11.200 --> 01:00:13.920
So think of an atom
vibrating in some well

01:00:13.920 --> 01:00:15.900
or against another atom.

01:00:15.900 --> 01:00:19.950
You probably need at least
10 discretization steps

01:00:19.950 --> 01:00:22.470
along that one vibration.

01:00:22.470 --> 01:00:24.870
So your time step is
of the order of 10

01:00:24.870 --> 01:00:26.410
to the minus 15 seconds--

01:00:26.410 --> 01:00:27.840
10 to the 14 seconds.

01:00:27.840 --> 01:00:29.608
That's sort of the
order of magnitude.

01:00:29.608 --> 01:00:31.650
For different materials
and different algorithms,

01:00:31.650 --> 01:00:32.550
it will be different.

01:00:32.550 --> 01:00:35.130
That's 10 femtoseconds.

01:00:35.130 --> 01:00:37.860
So you have to kind of do
an iteration step every 10

01:00:37.860 --> 01:00:39.150
femtoseconds.

01:00:39.150 --> 01:00:42.600
So that means even if you
do 100,000 time steps,

01:00:42.600 --> 01:00:45.820
you still only have
1 nanosecond of time.

01:00:45.820 --> 01:00:46.840
OK?

01:00:46.840 --> 01:00:48.400
And so you'll see typical--

01:00:48.400 --> 01:00:51.100
and these simulations are
in the order of picoseconds

01:00:51.100 --> 01:00:53.290
to 100 nanoseconds.

01:00:53.290 --> 01:00:56.440
Those are really
long simulations.

01:00:56.440 --> 01:01:00.880
And it's amazing, but you can
see a lot of important physics

01:01:00.880 --> 01:01:02.570
recurring on that
timescale-- sometimes

01:01:02.570 --> 01:01:07.030
the reaction between molecules
or absorption resorption

01:01:07.030 --> 01:01:08.950
phenomena.

01:01:08.950 --> 01:01:11.680
If you sort of want to do, and
the first thing you should do

01:01:11.680 --> 01:01:15.100
is a back-of-the-envelope
calculation is the phenomenon

01:01:15.100 --> 01:01:17.830
that I want to see,
or that I hope to see,

01:01:17.830 --> 01:01:20.560
does it live anywhere
near this time scale?

01:01:20.560 --> 01:01:22.600
And sometimes you can
give the system help.

01:01:22.600 --> 01:01:25.120
You can raise the
temperature, because stuff

01:01:25.120 --> 01:01:27.202
will happen faster.

01:01:27.202 --> 01:01:28.660
But you should
realize that there's

01:01:28.660 --> 01:01:32.590
certain stuff that you do not
see on this time scale at all.

01:01:32.590 --> 01:01:35.950
There are people who
study solidification out

01:01:35.950 --> 01:01:38.320
of liquids within d.

01:01:38.320 --> 01:01:40.390
And, you know, there
may be even some here.

01:01:40.390 --> 01:01:43.510
It's stupid period.

01:01:43.510 --> 01:01:46.930
You do not see anything
relevant on this time

01:01:46.930 --> 01:01:50.380
scale that has to do with
any real solidification.

01:01:50.380 --> 01:01:54.460
The only thing you can do is
enormously super cool a liquid,

01:01:54.460 --> 01:01:57.430
overdrive it, and
really sort of induce

01:01:57.430 --> 01:02:00.100
extremely fast crystallization
which has nothing

01:02:00.100 --> 01:02:02.170
to do with real solidification.

01:02:02.170 --> 01:02:07.400
And so the one example I
give is diffusion in solids.

01:02:07.400 --> 01:02:10.730
You can do dynamics
on fast diffusers,

01:02:10.730 --> 01:02:12.440
but most things are
not fast diffusers.

01:02:12.440 --> 01:02:13.378
So I did a--

01:02:13.378 --> 01:02:15.170
I show you the kind of
back-of-the-envelope

01:02:15.170 --> 01:02:18.020
calculation you should do.

01:02:18.020 --> 01:02:20.510
A diffusivity is a
length scale squared

01:02:20.510 --> 01:02:24.680
times the jump rate,
where a is essentially

01:02:24.680 --> 01:02:26.870
the distance which you jump.

01:02:26.870 --> 01:02:27.830
OK?

01:02:27.830 --> 01:02:32.420
So if you take a relatively fast
diffusion at room temperature

01:02:32.420 --> 01:02:35.120
10 to the minus 14 centimeters
squared per second,

01:02:35.120 --> 01:02:38.850
it's a respectable diffusivity
at room temperature.

01:02:38.850 --> 01:02:40.940
Most materials, you
would never see that.

01:02:40.940 --> 01:02:43.160
It's not quite a
fast diffuser yet.

01:02:43.160 --> 01:02:46.160
This number would be more
at 10 to the minus 11, 10

01:02:46.160 --> 01:02:48.110
to the minus 12.

01:02:48.110 --> 01:02:50.750
And you take a jump
length of 1 Angstrom.

01:02:50.750 --> 01:02:53.810
So that's 10 miles
18 centimeter.

01:02:53.810 --> 01:03:00.150
Then you can show that the jump
rate is about 100 per second.

01:03:00.150 --> 01:03:05.390
So if you have a 10 to
the minus 14 diffusivity,

01:03:05.390 --> 01:03:11.510
an atom jumps about 100 times
per second, or about 1 times

01:03:11.510 --> 01:03:14.070
per 10 milliseconds.

01:03:14.070 --> 01:03:16.550
So do you see now the
enormous disparity

01:03:16.550 --> 01:03:26.160
in time scale from 1
nanosecond to 10 milliseconds?

01:03:26.160 --> 01:03:29.960
So you could wait forever in
your dynamics to see things

01:03:29.960 --> 01:03:33.350
if you're sort of not smart.

01:03:33.350 --> 01:03:34.580
You'll see similar phenomena.

01:03:34.580 --> 01:03:36.440
Like, you could study.

01:03:36.440 --> 01:03:39.770
You could use dynamics to look
at, say, surface deposition.

01:03:39.770 --> 01:03:42.950
Let's say molecular beam
epitaxy or something

01:03:42.950 --> 01:03:45.770
like that where you lay
down layer by later.

01:03:45.770 --> 01:03:50.300
If you actually do the math
in a real MB experiment,

01:03:50.300 --> 01:03:52.950
you tend to lay down about
one layer per second.

01:03:52.950 --> 01:03:55.140
That's the order of magnitude.

01:03:55.140 --> 01:03:59.820
So you can actually never get
that by direct simulation.

01:03:59.820 --> 01:04:01.400
So what do people do?

01:04:01.400 --> 01:04:03.980
Well, people do the
short simulations

01:04:03.980 --> 01:04:08.090
to extract useful information
that they can then

01:04:08.090 --> 01:04:11.300
use in other models
to get the real time

01:04:11.300 --> 01:04:12.900
scales that they want.

01:04:12.900 --> 01:04:15.800
And so that's some of the
things we're going to teach you.

01:04:22.890 --> 01:04:23.480
OK.

01:04:23.480 --> 01:04:25.105
Probably going to
run out of time here.

01:04:25.105 --> 01:04:31.040
But the other option--

01:04:31.040 --> 01:04:32.390
so if you don't.

01:04:32.390 --> 01:04:34.160
If you cannot do the dynamics--

01:04:34.160 --> 01:04:36.320
is to use statistical
mechanics and sort of

01:04:36.320 --> 01:04:39.110
integrate as far of the
length scale and time scale

01:04:39.110 --> 01:04:40.340
as you can.

01:04:40.340 --> 01:04:44.420
And just those of you
who may have never seen

01:04:44.420 --> 01:04:50.060
statistical mechanics, I'm going
to now totally confuse you.

01:04:50.060 --> 01:04:54.620
But the essential ideas are
sort of in these four equations

01:04:54.620 --> 01:05:01.040
that you now consider
a macroscopic state

01:05:01.040 --> 01:05:03.470
as a collection of
microscopic states

01:05:03.470 --> 01:05:06.470
that you can
fluctuate in between.

01:05:06.470 --> 01:05:10.340
The probability for each
of these microscopic states

01:05:10.340 --> 01:05:13.490
is proportional to the
exponential of minus beta

01:05:13.490 --> 01:05:17.160
that the energy, and
beta is 1 over kT.

01:05:20.080 --> 01:05:21.730
So what does that mean?

01:05:21.730 --> 01:05:24.820
Microscopic states
with low energy

01:05:24.820 --> 01:05:28.330
show up with high probability,
and microscopic stage

01:05:28.330 --> 01:05:32.740
with high energy shell up with
with very low probability.

01:05:32.740 --> 01:05:34.780
Makes sense.

01:05:34.780 --> 01:05:37.480
The sum of all
these unnormalized

01:05:37.480 --> 01:05:40.780
probability terms is called
the partition function.

01:05:40.780 --> 01:05:43.180
And you can show that knowledge
of the partition function

01:05:43.180 --> 01:05:45.547
is exactly the same as
knowledge of the free energy.

01:05:45.547 --> 01:05:47.380
The free energy is
essentially the logarithm

01:05:47.380 --> 01:05:49.030
of the partition function.

01:05:49.030 --> 01:05:53.230
And the entropy is the product
of the probability times

01:05:53.230 --> 01:05:56.180
the log of the probability
summed over these things.

01:05:56.180 --> 01:05:59.110
And again, that makes
sense because if you

01:05:59.110 --> 01:06:03.700
are in one microscopic
state, then pi

01:06:03.700 --> 01:06:07.340
is 1 for that micro state
and 0 for all the other ones.

01:06:07.340 --> 01:06:09.280
So 1 log 1 0.

01:06:09.280 --> 01:06:10.990
And 0 log 0 is also 0.

01:06:10.990 --> 01:06:12.550
So your entropy is 0.

01:06:12.550 --> 01:06:15.160
So you have no disorder.

01:06:15.160 --> 01:06:17.350
So if your macroscopic
state leads

01:06:17.350 --> 01:06:20.770
to only one microscopic
realization that you can beam,

01:06:20.770 --> 01:06:22.060
then you have zero entropy.

01:06:22.060 --> 01:06:25.540
It's when you can be in multiple
different microscopic states

01:06:25.540 --> 01:06:27.460
that you have entropy.

01:06:27.460 --> 01:06:29.560
So you can think of
atomic vibrations,

01:06:29.560 --> 01:06:31.390
for example, as
really going between

01:06:31.390 --> 01:06:36.580
different microscopic states
of the positions of the atoms.

01:06:36.580 --> 01:06:38.080
You can think of
electronic entropy

01:06:38.080 --> 01:06:42.400
as going between different
electronic microscopic states.

01:06:52.440 --> 01:06:52.940
OK.

01:06:52.940 --> 01:06:54.315
So I want to show
you one example

01:06:54.315 --> 01:06:56.780
and probably end with that.

01:06:56.780 --> 01:06:58.790
Electronic entropy.

01:06:58.790 --> 01:07:00.470
It's one that, on
the face of it,

01:07:00.470 --> 01:07:03.305
looks very difficult
to deal with,

01:07:03.305 --> 01:07:05.180
because you have to deal
with the excitations

01:07:05.180 --> 01:07:06.210
of the electron.

01:07:06.210 --> 01:07:11.010
But actually in many cases it's
much easier than you think.

01:07:11.010 --> 01:07:13.040
If you solve the
Kohn-Sham equations,

01:07:13.040 --> 01:07:19.730
you get the eigenstates i and
the eigenvalues for the energy.

01:07:19.730 --> 01:07:21.860
And typically we
tend to treat these

01:07:21.860 --> 01:07:25.540
as one electron eigenstates.

01:07:25.540 --> 01:07:26.920
So we sort of fill--

01:07:26.920 --> 01:07:29.010
we think of filling these
with an electron, where

01:07:29.010 --> 01:07:30.843
we have a bunch of them,
and we fill them up

01:07:30.843 --> 01:07:32.460
to the Fermi level.

01:07:32.460 --> 01:07:35.582
There's actually nothing in
the theory of density function

01:07:35.582 --> 01:07:38.040
that tells you that they are
one-electron eigenstates where

01:07:38.040 --> 01:07:40.150
we treat them like that.

01:07:40.150 --> 01:07:42.810
So if you think of--

01:07:42.810 --> 01:07:45.990
I have a bunch of.

01:07:45.990 --> 01:07:48.580
Let's say I draw them
as discrete levels,

01:07:48.580 --> 01:07:50.550
a bunch of energy levels--

01:07:50.550 --> 01:07:51.528
E1, E2.

01:07:51.528 --> 01:07:53.070
And, of course, in
a solid, this will

01:07:53.070 --> 01:07:54.315
become a density of states.

01:07:57.460 --> 01:08:00.170
What's the level of uncertainty?

01:08:00.170 --> 01:08:02.350
What do I need to
know to characterize

01:08:02.350 --> 01:08:03.970
my electronic configuration?

01:08:03.970 --> 01:08:06.370
All I need to know is, is
the level occupied or not?

01:08:10.700 --> 01:08:12.770
So I can characterize
my electronic state

01:08:12.770 --> 01:08:15.560
by saying which levels
are occupied or not.

01:08:22.300 --> 01:08:24.637
So if you do this
on a solid now where

01:08:24.637 --> 01:08:26.470
you have a real density
of states-- and I've

01:08:26.470 --> 01:08:28.390
shown you one here.

01:08:28.390 --> 01:08:31.300
So this is a density
of electron states.

01:08:31.300 --> 01:08:33.189
This is energy.

01:08:33.189 --> 01:08:35.649
And forget the
bottom piece here.

01:08:35.649 --> 01:08:37.899
Just think of the top.

01:08:37.899 --> 01:08:39.410
These are actually
spin polarized.

01:08:39.410 --> 01:08:43.689
One is in the up dos,
and one is the down dos.

01:08:43.689 --> 01:08:45.550
So my Fermi level--

01:08:45.550 --> 01:08:46.990
I don't know.

01:08:46.990 --> 01:08:50.050
It's actually at 0 here, but
that makes it less interesting.

01:08:50.050 --> 01:08:55.819
Let me assume the Fermi
level is at minus 2 here.

01:08:55.819 --> 01:08:59.149
So at 0 temperature
I feel all the states

01:08:59.149 --> 01:09:01.040
below the Fermi level.

01:09:01.040 --> 01:09:03.160
OK?

01:09:03.160 --> 01:09:07.090
At elevated temperature, you
know you apply the Fermi-Dirac

01:09:07.090 --> 01:09:11.260
distribution function,
and so you'll

01:09:11.260 --> 01:09:15.200
have a filling that's
maybe a little different.

01:09:15.200 --> 01:09:16.700
And I'm kind of exaggerating.

01:09:16.700 --> 01:09:19.075
The width of the Fermi-Dirac
distribution function is not

01:09:19.075 --> 01:09:19.640
nearly--

01:09:19.640 --> 01:09:21.500
so it's 1 here and 0 here.

01:09:21.500 --> 01:09:24.979
It's not nearly as wide
at reasonable temperature.

01:09:24.979 --> 01:09:27.859
So how can you get the entropy?

01:09:27.859 --> 01:09:30.979
Well, you can get the
entropy from the probability

01:09:30.979 --> 01:09:34.819
that each electronic state
is filled or unfilled.

01:09:34.819 --> 01:09:35.600
OK?

01:09:35.600 --> 01:09:39.680
So if f is the probability
that it's filled--

01:09:39.680 --> 01:09:42.859
so this is the entropy coming
from when the state is filled,

01:09:42.859 --> 01:09:45.770
the entropy coming from
when the state is unfiled,

01:09:45.770 --> 01:09:49.729
and the sum over all
these possibilities

01:09:49.729 --> 01:09:52.560
is the electronic entropy.

01:09:52.560 --> 01:09:56.000
So if, in ab-initio calculation,
you calculate the density

01:09:56.000 --> 01:09:59.900
of states, you actually have
a trivial way of getting out

01:09:59.900 --> 01:10:02.090
the electronic entropy.

01:10:02.090 --> 01:10:04.430
And this is-- getting
the density of states

01:10:04.430 --> 01:10:06.510
is really rather simple.

01:10:06.510 --> 01:10:08.870
So you just smear it with
the Fermi-Dirac distribution

01:10:08.870 --> 01:10:11.060
function, and you sum--

01:10:11.060 --> 01:10:14.210
or you do this as an integral
typically rather than summing.

01:10:14.210 --> 01:10:19.490
And you have the
electronic entropy.

01:10:19.490 --> 01:10:22.500
It's very simple to do.

01:10:22.500 --> 01:10:26.660
So just as sort of a caution,
what I should tell you

01:10:26.660 --> 01:10:29.750
is that usually this
works very well,

01:10:29.750 --> 01:10:32.750
but the fundamental
underlying approximation

01:10:32.750 --> 01:10:35.190
lies in the starting point.

01:10:35.190 --> 01:10:38.060
It's in assuming
that the epsilon I's,

01:10:38.060 --> 01:10:42.020
or the eigenvalues,
are the eigenstates

01:10:42.020 --> 01:10:44.960
of the real electron system.

01:10:44.960 --> 01:10:46.910
So what I'm
essentially saying is

01:10:46.910 --> 01:10:50.900
that if you excite an
electron or remove one

01:10:50.900 --> 01:10:54.530
from the occupied states,
you're essentially

01:10:54.530 --> 01:10:58.100
perturbing the system exactly
by that energy of that state

01:10:58.100 --> 01:11:01.100
that I took out.

01:11:01.100 --> 01:11:03.890
If I have a Kohn-Sham
eigenvalue of 3 electron

01:11:03.890 --> 01:11:09.140
volts with some eigenstate, and
I put the electron in there,

01:11:09.140 --> 01:11:11.750
I'm assuming that that's
exactly the perturbation

01:11:11.750 --> 01:11:15.080
that a real electron
will do in the system.

01:11:15.080 --> 01:11:17.162
If you go back at the
theory of density function,

01:11:17.162 --> 01:11:18.620
there is nothing
in the theory that

01:11:18.620 --> 01:11:20.510
tells you that that's right.

01:11:20.510 --> 01:11:21.040
OK?

01:11:21.040 --> 01:11:24.680
Remember density function
theory is based on the density?

01:11:24.680 --> 01:11:28.640
And the Kohn-Sham idea was
essentially the smart way

01:11:28.640 --> 01:11:32.210
of writing the density in terms
of things that look like one

01:11:32.210 --> 01:11:36.530
electron orbital
but they aren't.

01:11:36.530 --> 01:11:37.190
OK?

01:11:37.190 --> 01:11:40.940
So an eigenstate
densely function theory

01:11:40.940 --> 01:11:43.400
is not a one-electron orbit.

01:11:43.400 --> 01:11:46.250
We just hope it is, and it
sometimes looks like it is.

01:11:46.250 --> 01:11:48.000
But it's not.

01:11:48.000 --> 01:11:51.740
And if it's not, then you
can describe excitations

01:11:51.740 --> 01:11:56.000
of electrons as going between
one Kohn-Sham eigenstate

01:11:56.000 --> 01:11:58.910
to another Kohn-Sham
eigenstate because they're not

01:11:58.910 --> 01:12:00.730
one electron eigenstate.

01:12:00.730 --> 01:12:01.250
OK?

01:12:01.250 --> 01:12:05.080
So what we are doing
is completely hokey.

01:12:05.080 --> 01:12:07.930
It's just that, in reasonable
materials and metals

01:12:07.930 --> 01:12:09.880
and semiconductors,
they don't look

01:12:09.880 --> 01:12:11.980
very much like
one-election eigenstate,

01:12:11.980 --> 01:12:13.780
and this stuff works.

01:12:13.780 --> 01:12:17.320
Where it breaks
down is typically

01:12:17.320 --> 01:12:19.690
in materials with very high
degrees of correlation,

01:12:19.690 --> 01:12:23.170
transition metal oxides, where
these things don't look at all

01:12:23.170 --> 01:12:24.580
like one-electron eigenstates.

01:12:24.580 --> 01:12:26.620
Because what happens in
those is, as soon as you

01:12:26.620 --> 01:12:31.020
do an electron excitation, the
whole underlying eigenvalue

01:12:31.020 --> 01:12:32.740
spectrum changes.

01:12:32.740 --> 01:12:33.240
OK?

01:12:33.240 --> 01:12:35.760
And remember then it's
not an eigenstate.

01:12:35.760 --> 01:12:39.880
An eigenstate is supposed to
be orthogonal to the rest.

01:12:39.880 --> 01:12:43.980
So if filling or
unfilling it changes

01:12:43.980 --> 01:12:45.507
the occupation of
all the other ones

01:12:45.507 --> 01:12:47.340
and the wave function
of all the other ones,

01:12:47.340 --> 01:12:50.250
then it wasn't an eigenstate.

01:12:50.250 --> 01:12:53.100
So there this stuff fails.

